review_blob: Pretty bronze color. Had to really stick my nose in to smell anything pumpkin-y, more warm spices (mostly nutmeg in mine) than the squash proper. Better than the other shock top offerings in my assortment and very nice, but if Id been set on a "pumpkin ale" Id have been disappointed. Its kind of interesting, though, more bitter than I expected and with a nice sweetness from the wheat.

Straw gold, very bright, tastes clean with lots of coriander and orange, but definitely a one trick pony. Theres a little bread flavor Id have enjoyed in greater quantity. Not bad at all, just perhaps a bit boring.

Pours a straw/gold with little head. Smells nice, kind of flowery and bright with some grainy scent, and tastes bready with bitter herbs. Not really a great example of a klsch, but the colder it gets, the better it tastes, and the best of my sixer was after a long drive in a hot car.

Nice cloudy gold. More clove than banana on this one, with citrus and bread. Body was lighter than I expected. Good carbonation, has some sweetness Ive missed on other hefeweizens recently, and a touch of bubblegum.

Orange/yellow with moderate head. Smells grassy, but has a nice bready flavor and light, buttery feel. Sharp and clean, nice for hot weather, but Im hung up on the name: this is too bitter on balance for it to be my session beer of choice, and it goes flat quickly. Still a good all-around from Saranacs summer pack.
Light grassy scent, gold in the glass. A little fruity to start, but the malt picks up. Not too heavily hopped, and ... sour, rather than sharp. Great hot weather beer.
Pours gold with little head. Light body, floral and a little citrusy. Nice clean grainy finish.
Bottled. Gold with minimal head. Light hoppy/floral scent. Bitter, but with a nice malt/rye aftertaste.
Cloudy dark orange. Yeasty resin, fresh, fruity, but with heavier taste than some other hefes. Metallic and hoppy. The smell is amazing.
Grapefruit to start, so bitter its almost acrid. Resinous, herbal, almost medicinal taste, with a clearer and more malty finish.
